### 2. Dataplane Enhancement Taxonomy
* **Presentation**: [02) Dataplane Enhancement Taxonomy](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-02-dataplane-enhancement-taxonomy-01)
* **Presented by**: Gihyeon Yi
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-dataplane-taxonomy`
* **Summary**:
  * Version 06 updates Section 8 ("Considerations for Interoperability between Solutions") to include complete tables. It aligns with terminology in `draft-ietf-detnet-multi-domain-framework` (specifically "technological domains").
  * Metrics for interoperability include "operability" (control plane integration ease) and "performance" (data plane capability to meet requested service levels).
  * The document is stable, and no further revisions are planned.
  * **Discussion**: Mike Blanche asked about the implementation implications of the low/medium/high interoperability levels. Gihyeon Yi clarified that as an informational document, its purpose is categorization and aiding understanding of current WG data plane solutions, rather than providing standard implementation details. Lou Berger welcomed list contributions to further refine the definitions.

### 3. Latency Guarantee with Stateless Fair Queuing
* **Presentation**: [03) Latency Guarantee with Stateless Fair Queuing](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-03-latency-guarantee-with-stateless-fair-queuing-00)
* **Presented by**: Gihyeon Yi
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-stateless-fair-queuing`
* **Summary**:
  * Adopted in April 2024. Revision 01 adds estimation of the total service rate of the link in Section 6.3 (admission control). It references the ITU-T draft "wider QS SRE RF" and introduces the required metadata along with header formats (Section 6.1 and 6.2).
  * Outlines coordination between ITU-T standards (high-level requirements) and IETF standards (RSVP, IPv6, MPLS MNA). It also includes a mathematical approximation technique for CSFQ using a rotating strict priority scheduler to reduce implementation complexity for high-speed routers.
  * **Discussion on ITU-T SG13 Coordination**:
    * Lou Berger stressed the importance of avoiding duplicate definitions between SDOs. The IETF work must align with the ITU-T base specifications, and any direct overlap will block publication at the IESG.
    * John Scudder (AD) strongly recommended resolving any overlap and clarifying SDO boundaries within the working group before the document is submitted to the IESG.
    * Mike Blanche pointed out that the ITU-T SG13 draft uses four metadata fields, whereas the IETF draft previously used three. Moving to four fixes the inconsistency but may affect older ITU-T recommendations that only reference three fields.
    * Tae Sung Chae (ITU-T SG13 Q6 Rapporteur) clarified that ITU-T focuses on high-level use cases, requirements, and framework architectures, whereas IETF defines protocol and data plane mechanisms. He noted that ITU-T delayed consenting their document to align with IETF's feedback.

### 4. Deadline Based Deterministic Forwarding
* **Presentation**: [06)  Deadline Based Deterministic Forwarding](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-06-deadline-based-deterministic-forwarding-00)
* **Presented by**: Peng Liu
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-deadline-based-forwarding`
* **Summary**:
  * Version 01 simplifies the document structure and defines key abbreviations (EDF, C-EDF).
  * Removed options involving reshaping to focus strictly on two stateless options for improved scalability: (1) latency compensation + sorting queue, and (2) latency compensation + RPQ (Rotating Priority Queue).

### 5. Timeslot Queueing and Forwarding Mechanism
* **Presentation**: [07) Timeslot Queueing and Forwarding Mechanism](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-07-timeslot-queueing-and-forwarding-mechanism-00)
* **Presented by**: Peng Liu
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-packet-timeslot-mechanism`
* **Summary**:
  * Version 01 adds an operational considerations section and moves evaluation details to the appendix. 
  * Removed PTM detection and global timeslots to focus strictly on BUM detection.
  * **Discussion**: Gihyeon Yi asked if the authors had considered merging this mechanism with TCQF (`draft-ietf-detnet-tcqf`). He noted that TCQF is class-based, whereas this mechanism is flow-based, making merging technically complex. Shaofu Peng commented that there are no major technical blockers to merging, and the decision rests with the working group. Lou Berger requested that Shaofu Peng post his detailed comments to the mailing list due to poor room audio.

### 6. On-time Forwarding with Push-In First-Out (PIFO) queue
* **Presentation**: [08) On-time Forwarding with Push-In First-Out (PIFO) queue](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-08-on-time-forwarding-with-push-in-first-out-pifo-queue-00)
* **Presented by**: Yun-Chul Liu
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-ontime-forwarding`
* **Summary**:
  * Version 02 introduces Appendix A, providing a mathematical proof of node-level and end-to-end delay bounds.
  * The algorithm organizes packets in ascending order based on their nominal departure time and guarantees departure before the maximum delay bound if admission conditions are met. Information was added regarding an FPGA implementation.

### 7. On-time Forwarding with Non-Work Conserving Stateless Core Fair Queuing
* **Presentation**: [10) On-time Forwarding with Non-Work Conserving Stateless Core Fair Queuing](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-10-on-time-forwarding-with-non-work-conserving-stateless-core-fair-queuing-00)
* **Presented by**: Yun-Chul Liu
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-nscore`
* **Summary**:
  * Version 02 introduces a new "arrival-based method" for calculating packet eligibility time (ET) and finish time (FT), alongside the existing direct method.
  * The arrival-based method uses local observed arrival times and scheduling gaps, eliminating the need for nodes to have explicit knowledge of clock differences or upstream propagation delays. Both C-Score and N-Score algorithms have been implemented on FPGA.

### 8. A Control Plane Framework for Multi-Domain Deterministic Networking (DetNet)
* **Presentation**: [11) A Control Plane Framework for Multi-Domain Deterministic Networking (DetNet)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-11-a-control-plane-framework-for-multi-domain-deterministic-networking-detnet-00)
* **Presented by**: Carlos Bernardos
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-multi-domain-framework`
* **Summary**:
  * This is the first update since adoption (v01). The core domain definitions, problem statement, and coordination models remain stable.
  * Key additions include new terminology for multi-domain admission control and cycle/slot synchronization. Two new functional requirements have been added: coordinating end-to-end admission control across all transit domains and aligning cycles/slots at boundaries. Section 5.2 was renamed to "Resource Reservation and Admission Control."
  * **Discussion**:
    * Gihyeon Yi noted that "time-bounded" solutions are not always slotted (some, like deadline-based EDF, are non-periodic). Carlos Bernardos agreed to clarify this.
    * Lou Berger (speaking as a contributor) cautioned against redefining existing terms such as "admission control" and "resource reservation" which are already defined in generic traffic engineering and DetNet architectures. He advised referencing existing RFC definitions or copying them verbatim.
    * Mike Blanche asked for clarification on what constitutes a "multi-domain" setup. Carlos Bernardos explained that the framework currently outlines three domain definitions (administrative, technological, and controller-based) and focuses heavily on controller-based boundaries.

### 9. Deterministic Networking SRv6 Data Plane for Service Protection
* **Presentation**: [12) Deterministic Networking SRv6 Data Plane for Service Protection](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-12-deterministic-networking-srv6-data-plane-for-service-protection-00)
* **Presented by**: Szilárd Kovács
* **Related Draft**: `draft-ietf-detnet-srv6-svc-protection`
* **Summary**:
  * Now adopted as a working group document. Explores using IPv6/SRv6 encapsulation to achieve redundancy and leverage SRv6 traffic engineering.
  * Two implementations are available:
    1. *Dependable Networking Toolkit*: A portable generic router/switch implementation in user-space with support for Layer 2 DetNet, Layer 3 MPLS, and SRv6.
    2. *XDP FRAIR*: An XDP-based high-performance TSN FRAIR implementation on Linux using SRv6 for disjoint paths.
  * Future plans include aligning with SRv6 segment and endpoint behaviors being defined in the SPRING WG and exploring integration with SRv6 L2/L3 VPNs.

### 10. Flow Aggregation for Enhanced DetNet
* **Presentation**: [13) Flow Aggregation for Enhanced DetNet](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-13-flow-aggregation-for-enhanced-detnet-00)
* **Presented by**: Gihyeon Yi
* **Summary**:
  * Version 05 changes the title to reflect its nature as a "Framework for Flow Aggregation in Scaling Deterministic Networks."
  * Key updates include: clarifying forwarding behavior of aggregate vs. member flows (using C-Score and N-Score examples), mapping data plane formats (including DSCP, MPLS TC, and MPLS MNA options), addressing aggregate-level vs. member-level admission control, and outlining control plane considerations (e.g., cross-domain parameter exchange and mapping DetNet flows to TSN streams).
  * **Discussion**:
    * János Farkas questioned the proposed use of BGP FlowSpec for mapping DetNet flows to TSN streams. Gihyeon Yi responded that it is intended as an option for cross-domain control plane signaling when traversing non-DetNet segments (e.g., TSN islands).
    * Lou Berger (speaking as a contributor) suggested integrating references to the existing `detnet-yang` model, which was specifically designed to support flow aggregation in the data plane, to describe how to manage aggregated flows.

### 11. Mechanism to Control Jitter Caused by Policing in DetNet
* **Presentation**: [14) Mechanism to control jitter caused by policing in Detnet](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-14-mechanism-to-control-jitter-caused-by-policing-in-detnet-00)
* **Presented by**: Shaofu Peng
* **Summary**:
  * Introduces a mechanism to control jitter introduced at the edge. Refactored the draft to replace "policing delay" with "ingress shaping delay" and related terms.
  * When traversing multiple technical domains, the draft suggests applying a single shaping policy across all domains rather than separate policies per domain, minimizing overall shaping delay.
  * **Discussion**: Gihyeon Yi questioned how the mechanism guarantees that the path delay stays below the end-to-end requirement. Shaofu Peng explained that the maximum shaping delay is factored in when calculating path routing. Gihyeon Yi pointed out that the concept heavily overlaps with the existing ADN draft and ITU-T standards, recommending that the author review them to avoid duplication.

### 12. Handling of Traffic Characteristic Deviation for DetNet
* **Presentation**: [15) Handling of traffic characteristic deviation for Detnet](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-15-handling-of-traffic-characteristic-deviation-for-detnet-00)
* **Presented by**: Zongpeng Du
* **Summary**:
  * Updated terminology from "anomalous traffic" to "traffic characteristic deviation" based on previous feedback. Addresses microburst accumulation in real-world networks due to variable packet lengths, coarse admission control, or overlapping aggregate flows.
  * Proposes two data plane handling policies: "squeezing" (temporarily delaying deviated packets to the next timeslot while keeping their identifiers) and "degrading" (directing packets to a lower priority queue and changing identifiers if deviations exceed a threshold). Safeguards include synchronization thresholds and exponential decay of squeezed capacity.
  * **Discussion**:
    * Gihyeon Yi agreed that burst accumulation is a valid issue but warned that squeezing or degrading policies could penalize innocent flows sharing the queue. He emphasized the need for proper flow isolation.
    * Lou Berger (speaking as a contributor) asked how "squeezing" conceptually differs from traditional "shaping" applied to a time-slotted queue. Zongpeng Du noted it provides a graceful fallback when shaping is absent or only coarse rate-limiting (CAR) is used. Lou Berger requested this discussion be taken to the mailing list.

### 13. PREOF Observability and OAM Requirements
* **Presentation**: [16) PREOF Observability and OAM Requirements](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-detnet-16-preof-observability-and-oam-requirements-00)
* **Presented by**: Luis M. Contreras
* **Summary**:
  * Identifies a gap in current OAM documents, which focus on service-level monitoring rather than PREOF (Packet Replication, Elimination, and Ordering Functions) behavior.
  * Proposes tracking specific events (replication, duplication elimination, reordering, timeouts, gap detection, late arrivals) and metrics (average/max reordering depth, holding times, recovery rates). Outlines six high-level requirements for reporting these statistics in a data-plane-agnostic manner.
  * **Discussion**:
    * Balázs Varga noted that because the WG only defines wire-format behavior and not internal algorithms, several proposed metrics (e.g., tracking packet path histories or internal reordering buffer depth) might be highly implementation- or algorithm-specific. He also requested clarification on how this draft relates to existing DetNet OAM documents.
    * Lou Berger agreed that while the high-level requirements are non-contentious, tracking granular sequence numbers or internal states at high speeds is practically difficult. He suggested distinguishing between "required" and "desired" parameters.
    * Gihyeon Yi asked for clarification on "packet discard" versus "duplicate elimination" in Requirement 3. Luis M. Contreras explained it differentiates packets discarded due to errors/buffer limits versus duplicate packets.
    * Balázs Varga and János Farkas mentioned that some of these counters are already defined in open-source PREOF implementations and in IEEE 802.1CB, which can serve as a useful baseline.

